                                                =======
                                                VECTOR
                                                =======




-> Implementation class of List interface.
-> Internal data structure is growable array.
-> Duplciates are allowed.
-> Insertion order preserved.
-> This is synchronized.
-> Vector is called legacy class(jdk 1.0 ).

-> To traverse vector we can use Enumeration as a cursor.
-> Enumenration is called as Legacy cursor(jdk 1.0).



  ========
  Example:
  ========

package Collections;
import java.util.Enumeration;
import java.util.Vector;

public class Demo {
	
	
	public static void main(String[] args) {
		
		Vector<Integer> v = new Vector<>();
		v.add(100);
		v.add(200);
		v.add(300);
		v.add(null);
		
		System.out.println(v);
		
		Enumeration<Integer> elements = v.elements();
		
		while(elements.hasMoreElements()) {
			
			System.out.println(elements.nextElement());
		}
		
	}

}


OUTPUT:
=======
        [100, 200, 300, null]
        100
        200
        300
        null


                                    ========
                                     STACK
                                    ========
-> LIFO----> Last In First Out

-> Implementation class of List interface.
-> Extending from vector class.
-> Data Structure of Stack is LIFO(last in first out).

push() --> to insert object
pop()  --> to get last element 
peek() --> to remove last element 


========
Example:
========

package Collections;

import java.util.Stack;

public class Demo {
	
	
	public static void main(String[] args) {
		
		
		Stack s = new Stack();
		
		s.push(100);
		s.push(200);
		s.push(300);
		s.push(400);
		
		
		System.out.println(s);
		System.out.println(s.peek());//will give the top element.
		System.out.println(s.pop());//remove top element and return that
		System.out.println(s);
		
		
		
	}

}

OUTPUT:
======
[100, 200, 300, 400]
400
400
[100, 200, 300]









